IRS990.MissionDesc: To foster stability and self-sufficiency of Bellevue's children and their families through programs that feed, clothe and educate.
IRS990.Desc: ASSIST:Emergency Assistance: Keeps kids stable and in their homes by providing food and basic needs, eviction prevention and utility shutoff prevention to families in crisis. For the year ended June 30, 2018, we provided rent assistance to 49 families and utility assistance to 59 families. Our pantry also provided assistance to 2,193 people by providing food, gift card for groceries, toiletries, school supples, quilts and misc items. Adopt-A-Family: Provides assistance by matching families in need with sponsors who provide food and gifts for Christmas. For the year ended June 30, 2018, we provided assistance for 352 families totaling 876 children and serving a total of 1,487 individuals.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: CLOTHING CHILDREN AND THEIR FAMILIES: Clothes-4-Kids Provides children with vouchers for new back-to-school clothes so they can begin their school year confident and ready to learn. For the year ended June 30, 2018, we were able to provide vouchers to 512 students helping 249 families. Thrift Culture The Bellevue LifeSpring Thrift Culture provides good-quality used clothing, shoes and household goods at affordable prices. Vouchers are given to families who cannot afford to pay. For the year ended June 30, 2018, we issued 17 coupons and 86 vouchers which provided assistance to 430 individuals.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: FEEDING CHILDREN AND THEIR FAMILIES: Breaktime-Mealtime (BTMT) The program distributes boxes of food during the school breaks for children enrolled in the federal free and reduced-price lunch program. For the year ended June 30, 2018, 7,011 children were served helping 3,455 families for a total of 99,320 meals. We also provide snacks for summer school. For the year ended June 30, 2018, we provided 4,309 packs for a total of 15,065 individual snacks.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part V, Line 4: Intended uses of the endowment fund.
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Board of Directors had designated unrestricted net assets as endowment funds to support the general mission of Bellevue LifeSpring.A donor contribution in fiscal year 2017 established a permanently restricted endowment fund to sustain the Organization into the future.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Grantmaker's Description of How Grants are Used
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Educational Grants Committee interviews candidates, determines eligibility and awards scholarship grants based on established criteria. Guidelines for providing emergency financial assistance to families in need have been developed and approved by the Board of Directors. The bulk of this assistance is provided in response to eviction or utility shut-off notices but may also include other financial assistance such as food, clothing, medical, child care, or auto repair. Recipients all receive an in-home visit by our social service administrator and must meet specific eligibility requirements based on demonstrated financial need.Additionally, clients are restricted in terms of how often they may apply for and receive financial assistance from the Organization.
